<Document>
<name>Mae Hong Son Loop</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Mae Hong Son Loop</h2><p><i>Northern Thailand · Chiang Mai loop via Pai, Mae Hong Son, Mae Sariang</i></p><p><b>1,864 curves around northwestern Thailand — Shan-influenced hill country, hot springs, hill-tribe villages.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>455 km (282 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>November–February (cool, clear); avoid the burning season (Mar–Apr) when air quality collapses</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Tight switchbacks (literally signposted at 1,864 curves); rain washouts in monsoon (Jul–Oct); livestock on road; fatigue from non-stop turns</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>1100</td></tr></table><hr><p>A 600 km loop from Chiang Mai through northwestern Thailand's mountain country — once a separate Shan-related kingdom, still distinct in its food, architecture, and ethnic mix (Shan, Karen, Lisu, Lahu, Hmong, Yao). The loop's official curve count, painted on shirts in every backpacker bar in Pai, is 1,864. The loop's highlight is arguably Pai itself — a once-tiny mountain village now a backpacker mainstay set in a beautiful valley — but the quieter half from Mae Hong Son south to Mae Sariang and over the back to Chiang Mai is the deeper experience. Stop at hot springs (Pong Dueat near Pai is the wildest), waterfalls (Mae Surin near Khun Yuam, a 100 m drop into a horseshoe valley), and roadside Shan-style markets at every village.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Pai</b> — Hippie-traveler hub in a green valley framed by limestone hills. Walking-street night market every evening. White Buddha (Wat Phra That Mae Yen) on the hill east of town has the long view at sunset.</li><li><b>Tham Lod (Lod Cave)</b> — 1.6 km river cave you traverse on a bamboo raft, guided by a lantern-bearer. Fossil teak coffins from a pre-historic culture (~1,200 BCE) sit on ledges inside. Swifts and bats at the entrances.</li><li><b>Mae Hong Son</b> — Provincial capital ringed by mountains. Wat Jong Klang and Wat Jong Kham reflected in Jong Kham lake form the postcard. Strong Shan/Burmese influence in temple architecture, food (khao soi here is exceptional).</li><li><b>Mae Surin Waterfall</b> — 100+ m single drop into a horseshoe valley — Thailand's most dramatic waterfall, but rarely visited because of the rough road. The view from the rim is the headline; the climb to the base is for the determined.</li><li><b>Khun Yuam</b> — Often-skipped town with a small WWII memorial museum about the Japanese army's catastrophic Burma retreat through these mountains in 1944–45 (40,000+ Japanese soldiers died in this district). Quietly moving.</li><li><b>Mae Sariang</b> — Mekong-tributary river town at the loop's south end. Salween River trips into the deep border country with Myanmar; Karen and Lawa villages in the surrounding mountains.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
