<Folder><name>Waypoints</name><Placemark><name>Mae Malai</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>98.850000,19.133300,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mae Taeng / Tha Pai hot springs</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>98.633300,19.200000,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Pai</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>98.437800,19.358900,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Soppong / Pang Mapha</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>98.284200,19.495300,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Tham Lod cave</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>98.176400,19.468900,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mae Hong Son</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>97.965600,19.301400,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mae Surin (Doi Mae U-Kho)</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>97.961400,19.063600,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Khun Yuam</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>97.941700,18.821700,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mae La Noi</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>97.873600,18.502800,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mae Sariang</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>97.933300,18.162200,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Hot</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>98.192500,17.883600,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder>
<Folder><name>Scenic Points</name><Placemark><name>Pai</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Hippie-traveler hub in a green valley framed by limestone hills. Walking-street night market every evening. White Buddha (Wat Phra That Mae Yen) on the hill east of town has the long view at sunset.]]></description><Point><coordinates>98.437800,19.358900,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Tham Lod (Lod Cave)</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[1.6 km river cave you traverse on a bamboo raft, guided by a lantern-bearer. Fossil teak coffins from a pre-historic culture (~1,200 BCE) sit on ledges inside. Swifts and bats at the entrances.]]></description><Point><coordinates>98.176400,19.468900,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mae Hong Son</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Provincial capital ringed by mountains. Wat Jong Klang and Wat Jong Kham reflected in Jong Kham lake form the postcard. Strong Shan/Burmese influence in temple architecture, food (khao soi here is exceptional).]]></description><Point><coordinates>97.965600,19.301400,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mae Surin Waterfall</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[100+ m single drop into a horseshoe valley — Thailand's most dramatic waterfall, but rarely visited because of the rough road. The view from the rim is the headline; the climb to the base is for the determined.]]></description><Point><coordinates>97.961400,19.063600,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Khun Yuam</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Often-skipped town with a small WWII memorial museum about the Japanese army's catastrophic Burma retreat through these mountains in 1944–45 (40,000+ Japanese soldiers died in this district). Quietly moving.]]></description><Point><coordinates>97.941700,18.821700,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mae Sariang</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Mekong-tributary river town at the loop's south end. Salween River trips into the deep border country with Myanmar; Karen and Lawa villages in the surrounding mountains.]]></description><Point><coordinates>97.933300,18.162200,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder>
</Document></kml>
